The authors present a case of a 55-year-old man complaining of right hip bulge and pain radiating to the lower extremity. There's no history of trauma. This patient underwent previous imaging follow-up due to a renal cell carcinoma with no evidence of recurrence. An old ischiatic heterotopic ossification is known.
 Imaging Findings: The imaging findings are described and highlighted in the discussion section.

Candidate diagnoses (choose ONE):
- Sarcoma (extraskeletal chondrosarcoma);
- Ischial apophyseal avulsion (hamstring avulsion)
- Myositis ossificans;
- Fratured ischial osteochondroma;
- Ischial apophyseal avulsion;
- Old ischial tuberosity fracture with degenerative changes;

Return exactly one option from the list above, copied verbatim.

The authors present a 33-year-old woman with a gradual onset of lower limb proximal muscle weakness since she was 3 years old. The diagnostic work up detected elevated creatinine kinase levels and dystrophic changes on muscle biopsy. There was no family history. Now she presents a myopathic walk with reduced lower limb mobility.
 Imaging Findings: We performed a MR scan on the patient. There was a symmetric generalised muscle atrophy with fatty replacement seen in the muscles of the thigh. The vastus lateralis muscles were particularly affected. There was relative sparing of the quadratus femoris, adductors, rectus femoris and gracilis muscles. Axial gadolinium enhanced images showed diffuse enhancement of all the thigh muscles relatively spared to the fatty infiltration. Hip joints were unremarkable and the underlying femur was normal.

